Common table expressions, subqueries, and sequel joins.

There are three ways that Spark sequel lets you compose more complex queries.

The first is common table expressions, written with the with-clause. A common table expression names an intermediate result, so that a complex query reads top-to-bottom, instead of inside-out. Spark supports full ansi with-chains.

The second is subqueries. Spark sequel supports both correlated and uncorrelated subqueries, in the where, from, and select clauses. A scalar subquery returns a single value. An in-subquery tests set membership. And an exists-subquery is correlated — the outer row passes if the inner query returns any matching row at all.

And the third is joins. All six join types are supported, with exactly the same semantics as the dataframe how-argument from earlier — just in sequel syntax. That is inner, left, right, and full-outer, plus left-semi and left-anti.

The takeaway is simple. Everything you already learned about dataframe joins and set logic applies here, unchanged. Only the syntax is different.
